{"title_page": "Chapli kebab", "text_new": "<span class=\"plainlinks\"></span>{{Infobox prepared food|name=Chapli kebab|image=Chapli Kabab.JPG|image_size=250px|caption=A plate of chicken chapli kebabs with garnish|alternate_name=Peshawari kebab\n|country=[[Pakistan]]\n|national_cuisine=[[Pakistani cuisine|Pakistani]],<ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/> [[Afghan cuisine|Afghan]],<ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/> [[Indian cuisine|Indian]]<ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/>\n|course=Appetiser, main course or side dish\n|type=[[Kebab]]\n|served=\n|main_ingredient=[[Ground meat|Minced]] [[Ground beef|beef]], [[Lamb and mutton|mutton]], or [[chicken as food|chicken]] \n|minor_ingredient=Various herbs and spices\n|similar_dish=[[Seekh kebab]]}}\n[[File:Chapli Kebab.jpg|thumb|Chapli kebab served at a [[Balti Triangle|Balti restaurant]] in Birmingham, UK.]]\n'''Chapli kebab''' ({{lang-ps|\u0686\u067e\u0644\u064a \u06a9\u0628\u0627\u0628}}){{efn-lg|{{lang-ur|{{nq|\u0686\u067e\u0644\u06cc \u06a9\u0628\u0627\u0628}}}}}}{{efn-lg|{{lang-hi|\u091a\u092a\u0932\u0940 \u0915\u092c\u093e\u092c}}}} is a [[Mughlai cuisine|Mughlai]]-influenced [[Pashtun cuisine|Pashtun]]-style [[Ground meat|minced]] [[kebab]], usually made from ground [[Ground beef|beef]], [[Lamb and mutton|mutton]] or [[chicken as food|chicken]] with various spices in the shape of a [[patty]]. It originates from [[Peshawar]], what is today northwest [[Pakistan]], and is also known as the '''Peshawari kebab'''.<ref name=\"NDTV\">{{cite web|url=http://food.ndtv.com/recipe-peshawari-chappali-kebab-171627|title=Peshawari Chappali Kebab|work=NDTV Food|accessdate=25 July 2016|first=Divya|last=Burman}}</ref><ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/>\n\nThe chapli kebab is a popular barbecue and street food throughout [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] and other parts of [[Pakistan]], as well as in eastern [[Afghanistan]] and [[India]].<ref name=\"Tirmizi\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1093949|title=Food Stories: Chapli kabab|work=Dawn|date=19 March 2014|accessdate=25 July 2016|first=Bisma|last=Tirmizi|quote=The province formerly known as NWFP and the eastern region of Afghanistan can proudly lay claim to the spicy flat meat beef patty, however, it stands as a favourite throughout Pakistan and India.}}</ref> In India, it is eaten as a regular street food, specifically, in the Indian cities of [[Bhopal]], [[Lucknow]], [[Delhi]] and [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]]; it is especially popular with [[Indian Muslim]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/chapli-kebab-1771609}}</ref> It can be served and eaten hot with [[naan]] bread, rice, or in buns and sandwiches such as in a [[bun kebab]].<ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/>\n\n==Origins==\n[[Mughlai cuisine|Mughal culinary influences]] in the region popularised a number of kebab dishes, resulting in local recipes such as the chapli kebab.<ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/> The name ''chapli'' is said to be derived from the [[Pashto]] word ''chaprikh'', meaning \"flat\" \u2013 alluding to the kebab's light, round and flattened texture.<ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/> Another theory is that the name is derived from ''[[Peshawari chappal|chappal]]'', the local word for sandals \u2013 implying the average shape and size of a kebab, which resembles that of a front part of the chappal sole.<ref>{{cite book|title=Culture Shock!: Pakistan|first=Karin|last=Mittmann|first2=Zafar|last2=Ihsan|publisher=Graphic Arts Center Publishing Company|date=1991|isbn=9781558680593|page=[https://archive.org/details/cultureshock00mitt/page/104 104]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/cultureshock00mitt/page/104}}</ref>\n\nThe city of Peshawar, where the recipe took hold, has over 2,000 kebab houses that serve the chapli kebab.<ref name=\"Dawn\"/> Such eateries have rapidly expanded in other cities as well. Today, the chapli kebab is featured on the menu of South Asian restaurants across the world.<ref name=\"Dawn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1049405|title=On the menu: Krazy about (Chapli) kebab|work=Dawn|first=Sher Alam|last=Shinwari|date=13 October 2013|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Ingredients and preparation==\nThe chapli kebab is prepared with raw, marinated mince and the meat can be either beef or lamb/mutton. The main ingredients include [[wheat flour]], different herbs and spices such as [[chili powder]], [[coriander]] leaves, followed by smaller quantities of onions, tomatoes, eggs, ginger, coriander or cumin seeds, green chillies, [[corn starch]], salt and pepper, baking powder, as well as a seasoning of [[lemon juice]] or [[pomegranate]] seeds.<ref name=\"NDTV\"/><ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/>\n\nThe kebabs can be fried shallow or deep in vegetable cooking oil over medium heat. Some chefs fry the kebabs in [[Animal fat|lamb fat]] over wood-fired stoves to lend an organic flavour. This approach is avoided by other gastronomists, citing health-conscious reasons.<ref name=\"Malik\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1196602|title=Khyber\u2019s most delicious export|work=Dawn|first=Shiza|last=Malik|date=27 July 2015|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Serving==\nOnce cooked, chapli kebabs can be served and [[garnish (food)|garnished]] with parsley, chopped onions and tomatoes, along with other accompaniments such as various [[chutney]] sauces, salad, yoghurt, [[South Asian pickles|pickles]] or nuts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/2Bj8sTJClD92JQf38fg201B/beef-chapli-kebab-with-pomegranate-chutney|title=Beef chapli kebab with pomegranate chutney|work=BBC Radio 4|first=Sumayya|last=Usmani|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fgWrCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA102|title=The Multicultural Cookbook for Students|first=Lois Sinaiko|last=Webb|first2=Lindsay Grace|last2=Roten|page=102|publisher=ABC-CLIO|date=2009|isbn=9780313375590}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://images.dawn.com/news/1175050|title=Weekend grub: Could these chapli kebabs from Peshawar be the best in Pakistan?|work=Dawn|first=Bilal|last=Agha|date=25 March 2016|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref> The chapli kebab is best served aromatic, moist and spicy.<ref name=\"Dupree\">{{cite book|title=Afghanistan|first=Louis|last=Dupree|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=9781400858910|date=2014|page=231}}</ref> It is considered a specialty of Pashtun cuisine and often served to guests.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/337139/comfort-food-keeping-warm-with-kebabs/|title=Comfort food: Keeping warm with kebabs|first=Fazal|last=Khaliq|work=The Express Tribune|date=16 February 2012|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref> The kebab is commonly consumed in meals with bread such as naan, rice dishes such as [[Kabuli pulao]], or wrapped in fast food.<ref name=\"Dawn\"/> In winters, green tea such as [[kahwah]] may traditionally be served alongside it, while cold drinks are preferred in the summers.<ref name=\"Dawn\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* [[List of kebabs]]\n* [[Pashtun cuisine]]\n* [[Pakistani fast food]]\n* [[Pakistani meat dishes]]\n*[[Afghan cuisine]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-lg}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Pakistani dishes}}\n{{Street food}}\n\n[[Category:Appetizers]]\n[[Category:Beef dishes]]\n[[Category:Goat dishes]]\n[[Category:Kebabs]]\n[[Category:Lamb dishes]]\n[[Category:Pakistani fast food]]\n[[Category:Pakistani meat dishes]]\n[[Category:Pashtun cuisine]]\n[[Category:Street food in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Food Watchlist Articles]]\n[[Category:Ground meat]]\n[[Category:Indian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Afghan cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "<span class=\"plainlinks\"></span>{{Infobox prepared food|name=Chapli kebab|image=Chapli Kabab.JPG|image_size=250px|caption=A plate of chicken chapli kebabs with garnish|alternate_name=Peshawari kebab\n|country=[[South Asia]]<ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/> \n|national_cuisine=[[Pakistani cuisine|Pakistani]],<ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/> [[Afghan cuisine|Afghan]],<ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/> [[Indian cuisine|Indian]]<ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/>\n|course=Appetiser, main course or side dish\n|type=[[Kebab]]\n|served=\n|main_ingredient=[[Ground meat|Minced]] [[Ground beef|beef]], [[Lamb and mutton|mutton]], or [[chicken as food|chicken]] \n|minor_ingredient=Various herbs and spices\n|similar_dish=[[Seekh kebab]]}}\n[[File:Chapli Kebab.jpg|thumb|Chapli kebab served at a [[Balti Triangle|Balti restaurant]] in Birmingham, UK.]]\n'''Chapli kebab''' ({{lang-ps|\u0686\u067e\u0644\u064a \u06a9\u0628\u0627\u0628}}){{efn-lg|{{lang-ur|{{nq|\u0686\u067e\u0644\u06cc \u06a9\u0628\u0627\u0628}}}}}}{{efn-lg|{{lang-hi|\u091a\u092a\u0932\u0940 \u0915\u092c\u093e\u092c}}}} is a [[Mughlai cuisine|Mughlai]]-influenced [[Pashtun cuisine|Pashtun]]-style [[Ground meat|minced]] [[kebab]], usually made from ground [[Ground beef|beef]], [[Lamb and mutton|mutton]] or [[chicken as food|chicken]] with various spices in the shape of a [[patty]]. It originates from [[Peshawar]], what is today northwest [[Pakistan]], and is also known as the '''Peshawari kebab'''.<ref name=\"NDTV\">{{cite web|url=http://food.ndtv.com/recipe-peshawari-chappali-kebab-171627|title=Peshawari Chappali Kebab|work=NDTV Food|accessdate=25 July 2016|first=Divya|last=Burman}}</ref><ref name=\"Tirmizi\"/>\n\nThe chapli kebab is a popular barbecue and street food throughout [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]] and other parts of [[Pakistan]], as well as in eastern [[Afghanistan]] and [[India]].<ref name=\"Tirmizi\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1093949|title=Food Stories: Chapli kabab|work=Dawn|date=19 March 2014|accessdate=25 July 2016|first=Bisma|last=Tirmizi|quote=The province formerly known as NWFP and the eastern region of Afghanistan can proudly lay claim to the spicy flat meat beef patty, however, it stands as a favourite throughout Pakistan and India.}}</ref> In India, it is eaten as a regular street food, specifically, in the Indian cities of [[Bhopal]], [[Lucknow]], [[Delhi]] and [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]]; it is especially popular with [[Indian Muslim]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=